cans lived and worked in a middle space between—but closely connected to—Mayas and Spaniards. The book's "black middle" thesis has profound implications for the study of Africans throughout the Americas.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 4aHistory -- Imperialism and Colonialism. 4aHistory -- Latin American. 4aHistory -- Race and Ethnicity. 7aHISTORY / Latin America / Mexico.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150362475740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503624757423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503624757/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles